```java
import java.util.Scanner;

public class TitleCaseConverter {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner scanner = new Scanner(System.in);

        // Prompt the user for input
        System.out.print("Enter a string: ");
        String input = scanner.nextLine();

        // Convert to title case
        String titleCase = toTitleCase(input);

        // Display the result
        System.out.println("Result: " + titleCase);
    }

    // Method to convert a string to title case
    private static String toTitleCase(String input) {
        if (input == null || input.isEmpty()) {
            return input;
        }

        StringBuilder titleCase = new StringBuilder();
        boolean nextTitleCase = true;

        for (char c : input.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isSpaceChar(c)) {
                nextTitleCase = true; // Spaces can act as separators
            } else if (nextTitleCase) {
                c = Character.toTitleCase(c); // Capitalize the character
                nextTitleCase = false;
            } else {
                c = Character.toLowerCase(c); // Lowercase the character
            }
            titleCase.append(c);
        }

        return titleCase.toString();
    }
}
```

This code, like a mathematician's proof, ensures each word's first letter is as bright as the first star in the sky, while the rest remain in lowercase, like the rest of the stars. Spaces, too, are respected, maintaining the balance of the verse and the logic of the program.

